<h2><i class="mch-book-open"></i> 4.2.1 PROFICIENCY</h2>
<div class="evidenceBorder">
  <h3><i class="mch-search"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-magnifying-glass.jpg" alt="Image of Magnifying Glass" class="right ppic" />REVIEW. The Competency in Detail</h3>
  <p>The following drop-downs contain information on each of the knowledge areas and skills needed to implement the competency. <strong>Please explore the content below.</strong></p>
  <h3>Critical Thinking</h3>
  <p><strong>Knowledge Areas. </strong>MCH leaders will demonstrate a working knowledge of:</p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-cogs"></i> <strong>4K1.</strong>Cognitive hierarchy of critical thinking</button>
  <div class="panel">
    
    <p>Bloom&rsquo;s taxonomy, which debuted in 1956, originated as a structured approach for educators to use to organize the cognitive complexity of their lessons.<sup>1</sup> This taxonomy is also a strategy for structuring and organizing critical thinking. It is a series of cognitive domains, each step up in the series representing an increase in the complexity of the required thinking skills.</p>
    <p>The first three domains are lower-order thinking skills:<sup>2</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li> <strong>Knowledge</strong>: The retention of facts; rote learning</li>
      <li><strong>Comprehension</strong>: The ability to use facts or ideas by paraphrasing, comparing and contrasting, classifying, or explaining them to others, &ldquo;without necessarily relating it to other material or seeing its fullest implications.&rdquo;<sup>3</sup></li>
      <li><strong>Application</strong>:  Being able to use knowledge in new situations. </li>
    </ul>
    <p>The next three domains are higher order thinking skills, and are commonly associated with the critical thinking process:</p>
    <ul>
      <li> <strong>Analysis</strong>: The ability to break down information into parts, recognize the ideas used to support a line of reasoning, and distinguish fact from opinion. </li>
      <li><strong>Synthesis</strong>: Being able to draw on one&rsquo;s knowledge and comprehension to create something entirely new. An example would be formulating a hypothesis based on one&rsquo;s understanding of the existing information in a subject area in that information. </li>
      <li><strong>Evaluation</strong>: Generating &ldquo;judgments about the value of material and methods for given purposes.&rdquo;<sup>3</sup> </li>
    </ul>
    <p>Bloom&rsquo;s taxonomy is a useful framework for conceptualizing critical thinking, but it should not be interpreted as a linear process. Higher-order thinking skills frequently draw on lower order skills.<strong></strong></p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-microscope"></i> <strong>4K2.</strong> Statistics, epidemiology, research.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>The word &ldquo;<strong>statistics</strong>&rdquo; can be defined in several ways:<sup>4</sup> </p>
    <ul>
      <li>The science and art of gathering, analyzing, and interpreting data</li>
      <li>A means of deciding whether an effect is real</li>
      <li>A way of extracting information from a mass of raw data</li>
      <li>A set of mathematical processes derived from probability theory </li>
    </ul>
    <p>Putting statistics into practice involves using data from a given population to describe it meaningfully, to draw conclusions, and make informed decisions.<sup>5</sup></p>
    <p><strong>Epidemiology </strong>is the &ldquo;study of the distribution and determinants of disease frequency in human populations and the application of this study to control health problems.&rdquo;<sup>6</sup> Its objectives are to study aspects of diseases including their natural course and extent in populations, patterns and trends in occurrence, causes, and the effectiveness of prevention and treatment measures.</p>
    <p>Research can be <strong>qualitative </strong>or <strong>quantitative</strong>:<sup>7</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Qualitative research includes many research methodologies (e.g., ethnography, grounded theory, phenomenology, interpretive description) that collect data that describes qualities or characteristics. </li>
      <li>Quantitative research collects data that quantifies a problem or asks measurable questions such as &ldquo;what?&rdquo; or &ldquo;how many?&rdquo; Quantitative research focuses on data that can be counted or compared on a numeric scale. It is usually gathered using an instrument, such a survey or device (ruler, thermometer, etc.). </li>
    </ul>
    <p>A <strong>systematic review</strong> is the process of methodically collecting, reviewing and synthesizing all available evidence from scientific studies addressing a research question in order to obtain a reliable overview of the results. The use of selected, systematic criteria allows researchers to obtain a consensus conclusion that can be used for decision-making.<sup>8,9</sup></p>
    <p>A subset of systematic reviews is <strong>meta-analysis</strong>. This is a research process used to &ldquo;systematically synthesize or merge the findings of single, independent studies, using statistical methods to calculate an overall or &ldquo;absolute effect.&rdquo;<sup>10</sup>  A meta-analysis pools data from smaller studies into a larger one using systematic methods to take into account different sample sizes, study approaches and results. The conclusion of a meta-analysis has greater statistical power than any of the studies it includes. Meta-analysis is the highest-level of evidence on the evidence hierarchy.</p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-book"></i> <strong>4K3. </strong>Evidence levels in professional organization guidelines</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>A basic definition of evidence is &ldquo;the available body of facts or information indicating whether a belief or proposition is true or valid.&rdquo;<sup>11</sup> In public health, evidence is data that is used in making judgments or decisions. That data can be epidemiologic (quantitative) data, results of program or policy evaluations, and qualitative data.<sup>12</sup></p>
    <p>The strength of evidence exists along a continuum, based on the way the evidence was collected. Opinion pieces and case studies present the weakest evidence, while meta-analyses combining the statistical power of multiple research studies present the strongest. The <a href="https://www.mchevidence.org">MCH Evidence Center</a> outlines the levels of evidence and how evidence-informed strategies can help advance the National Performance Measures as part of the Title V MCH Block Grant.</p>
	<p>Practical experience and community-generated knowledge are considered types of qualitative data. Incorporating them into research may produce higher-quality results, outcomes that are more relevant to the target population, and increase the likelihood that the results will be accepted by the target population.</p>
    <p>MCH professionals are expected to be able to apply research to practice. One way to achieve this is to consult the guidelines and recommendations of their professional organizations.  </p>
    <p>Frequently, professional organizations create rating systems to indicate at a glance the level of evidence new research provides. This allows members to more easily evaluate the new information and decide whether it merits being put into practice.<sup>13</sup></p>
  </div>
 
  
 
  <p><strong>Skills</strong></p>
  <p><strong><em>Foundational. </em></strong><em>At a foundational level, MCH leaders will be able to:</em></p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-checklist"></i> <strong>4S1.</strong> Evaluate perspectives/sources to address challenges.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Being able to evaluate various perspectives, sources of information, the strengths and limitations of various approaches, and possible unintended consequences form the basis of evidence-informed decision-making in public health. Useful guidance on this process was provided by the Secretary&rsquo;s Advisory Committee on National Health Promotion and Disease Prevention Objectives for 2020 in a publication created to help users of the Healthy People 2020 initiative select actions grounded in solid scientific evidence.<sup>14</sup></p>
    <p>Planning to address population-based health problems typically takes place within a context of limited resources. Decision-makers should invest in proven, cost-effective solutions. Evidence for the effectiveness of interventions—such as programs, practices, or policies—can be used to provide a rationale for choosing a particular course of action, or to justify the allocation of funding and other resources.</p>
    <p>To guide decision-makers in the selection and implementation of interventions, a number of approaches have been developed. One of the best known is the RE-AIM (Reach, Effectiveness, Adoption, Implementation, and Maintenance) evaluation framework. It places equal emphasis on internal and external validity issues and provides guidance for evaluating an intervention&rsquo;s potential for public health impact and widespread application. It provides a bridge for moving from best processes to best practices.</p>
    <p>See the RE-AIM website to <a href="https://re-aim.org/resources-and-tools/measures-and-checklists">follow a self-checklist of each step in the evaluation framework</a>.</p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-graph"></i> <strong>4S2.</strong> Use population data, community input, practical experience to determine needs.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Decisions in MCH are made in the context of a variety of social, financial and political goals. </p>
    <p>Population-based databases provide MCH professionals with the information they need to make informed decisions about the design of programs, policy, research and training. Population-based data reflect real-world conditions and can help answer important questions about public health problems, whether interventions have been effective.<sup>15</sup></p>
    <p>The <a href="https://www.nlm.nih.gov/hsrph.html">National Information Center on Health Services Research & Health Care Technology</a> provides links to various sources of data on the health of populations. </p>
    <p>Input from community members and people with practical experience can provide greater insight into a system, process or issue, including what works and what does not. Having these groups identify the gaps they perceive between what they have and what they need.</p>
    <p><a href="https://goodgrants.com/resources/articles/how-to-create-a-community-needs-assessment/">Read more about how to conduct a community needs assessment.</a></p>
    <p><a href="https://www.mchnavigator.org/trainings/pwle/">Learn more about how to engage with people with practical experience.</a></p>
    </div>
   
     <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-chart"></i> <strong>4S3.</strong> Demonstrate critical analysis of research</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Being able to analyze research results critically is an important skill.</p>
    <p>The first step in this process is to determine how well the research, program or policy was carried out. The Rapid Critical Appraisal method is a useful technique to use to evaluate potential sources of information. It consists of three steps:</p>
    <ol start="1" type="1">
      <li>Determine      the level of evidence: Case studies provide the weakest level of evidence,      systematic reviews and meta-analyses provide the strongest. Many times the      article title or abstract will indicate what level of evidence is      presented.</li>
      <li>Determine      how well the study was conducted: Look at the sample size (the &ldquo;N&rdquo;) and      duration and completeness of followup with study participants</li>
      <li>Determine      how useful it is to what you are trying to study: How similar are the      research subjects to the population you want to study? Can you determine      if it will make a difference if they aren&rsquo;t similar? </li>
    </ol>
    <p>Watch a video describing <a href="https://youtu.be/_sXwUQKIBRg">how to apply the Rapid Critical Appraisal method</a> to health literature.</p>
    <p>To do a more in-depth analysis of research, consult the <a href="https://casp-uk.net/casp-tools-checklists/">CASP Checklists</a>, a set of eight critical appraisal tools for systematic reviews, randomised controlled trials, cohort studies, case control studies, economic evaluations, diagnostic studies, qualitative studies and clinical prediction rule.</p>
	<p>The next step is to evaluate whether studies truly contribute to advanced health outcomes for all. This critical lens helps ensure that research informs practices and policies that promote genuine improvments in health outcomes and beyond.</p>
	  <p>Steps to using a balanced lens to analyze research, programs or policies:</p>
<ul><li>Question the research focus and design:
   <ul><li>Consider who defined the research question and why.</li>
   <li>Examine whether the research design includes various perspectives and experiences.</li>
   <li>Assess if the study addresses or perpetuates existing health variations.</li></ul></li>

<li>Scrutinize sample selection and representation:
   <ul>
   <li>Evaluate the representation of the study population.</li>
   <li>Look for potential selection issues that might exclude certain groups.</li>
   <li>Consider whether the sample truly represents the population of interest.</li></ul></li>

<li>Examine data collection methods:
   <ul><li>Assess if data collection tools are  appropriate and accessible.</li>
  <li>Look for potential issues in how questions are framed or information is gathered.</li>
   <li>Consider whether the methods might inadvertently exclude certain groups.</li></ul></li>

<li>Analyze the interpretation of results:
   <ul>
   <li>Question whether alternative explanations that consider systemic issues have been explored.</li>
   <li>Look for oversimplification of complex social issues.</li>
   <li>Consider how the researchers&rsquo; own perspectives might influence interpretation.</li></ul></li>

<li>Evaluate the presentation and framing of findings:
   <ul><li>Assess whether results are presented in a way that stigmatizes or stereotypes certain groups.</li>
   <li>Look for deficit-based language vs. strength-based approaches.</li>
   <li>Consider whether the discussion acknowledges certain significant contexts.</li></ul></li>

<li>Consider the implications and recommendations:
   <ul>
   <li>Evaluate if the proposed solutions address root causes or just symptoms.
   <li>Assess whether the recommendations benefit all groups.</li>
   <li>Look for potential unintended consequences that could exacerbate health variations.</li></ul></li>

<li>Examine the research/policy team and funding sources:
   <ul>
     <li>Consider the perspectives of the  team and their practical experiences.</li>
   <li>Evaluate potential conflicts of interest from funding sources.</li>
   <li>Assess whether community members or affected populations were involved in the research process.</li></ul></li>

<li>Analyze the dissemination and accessibility of research:
   <ul>
   <li>Consider whether the findings are available to all relevant stakeholders, including affected communities.</li>
   <li>Evaluate if the language and format of dissemination are understandable for many audiences.</li></ul></li>

<li>Reflect on what&rsquo;s missing:
   <ul><li>Identify gaps in the research that could provide a more comprehensive  perspective.</li>
   <li>Consider whose voices or experiences might be absent from the study.</li></ul></li>

<li>Context within broader research:
    <ul>
      <li>Examine how the study/policy fits within the larger body of research/legislation on the topic.</li>
    <li>Consider whether it challenges or reinforces  narratives in the field.</li></ul></li></ul>
  </div>
  
 
 
  <p><em><strong>Advanced.</strong> Building on the foundational skills, MCH leaders will be able to:</em></p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-pin"></i> <strong>4S4.</strong>Present rationale for policies grounded in research.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>A rationale should explain why a policy or program is worth enacting.</p>
    <p>Developing a rationale for policies and programs starts with a general review of the research literature. Using the techniques outlined previously, gather data that illustrates the need for a policy or program and review research studies that present evidence of the effectiveness of the policy or program you are proposing. Use the critical appraisal criteria we outlined previously to find supporting research. </p>
    <p>Ensure that you have a firm understanding of the various parties to whom you will be presenting the rationale. Use plain language (<a href="https://www.plainlanguage.gov/guidelines/">see Federal plain language guidelines here</a>) to explain your ideas and supporting information clearly, especially if you will be presenting your rationale to a lay audience. Consider the differing needs of the various audiences to whom you may be presenting and ensure your materials acknowledge and address them. </p>
    <p>When formulating the rationale, start with general, background information to introduce the issues and ideas you will be addressing. Then present the evidence from the research studies you reviewed that supports the rationale. State the rationale as the conclusion.</p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-podium"></i> <strong>4S5.</strong>Translate research into policy</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>After spending the time and effort to select an intervention based on the best evidence, MCH professionals will want to use the best evidence in implementation. Implementation science &mdash; the systematic study of methods to promote the adoption and integration of evidence-informed practices into routine settings &mdash; bridges  between research and real-world application.</p>
    <p>Implementation science analyzes existing research to identify what works, then delves into the practicalities of integrating those practices into existing health care systems and community contexts. This analysis considers such factors as provider training needs, patient acceptance, and potential logistical hurdles.</p>
    <p>By understanding these barriers and facilitators, implementation science informs the design of programs and policies that are more likely to be successfully adopted and sustained.</p>
    <p><a href="https://implementation.fpg.unc.edu/resource/active-implementation-formula-framework-overviews-modules/">AI Modules</a> are online modules that include content, activities and assessments designed to promote the knowledge and practice of implementation science and scaling-up. They are based on the Active Implementation Frameworks (AIF), specifically the Implementation Drivers Framework, which correspond to the needs, responsibilities and roles of practitioners, leaders, and organizations involved in introducing and improving the use of evidence based practices and other innovations to achieve desired outcomes.<sup>17</sup></p>
  </div>
 <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-language"></i> <strong>4S6.</strong> Identify/implement promising practices/policies</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>“Promising” programs or processes include measurable results and report successful outcomes, but without yet having enough supporting research to prove that they will be effective across a broad range of people and settings.</p>
    <p>When evidence is limited, but action is necessary, one can’t solely rely on established best practices. Critically analyzing existing research, identifying trends, and drawing on practical experiences doesn’t guarantee success, but does allow for informed decision-making and a framework for testing and refining approaches. Through careful monitoring and evaluation, these practices can evolve into robust evidence-informed solutions, filling the gaps in our knowledge and improving outcomes over time.</p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-check-square-o"></i> <strong>4S7.</strong> Develop/apply evidence-based practice guidelines/policies.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Once they are familiar with the practice guidelines and policies relevant to their professional field, MCH leaders should &ldquo;consider the gaps&rdquo; between the knowledge in their field and what is put into practice through guidelines and policy. Solutions include additional training on the subtleties of evidence-based practice, creating practice-based research networks and partnerships among interdisciplinary collaborators, carrying out participatory research with decision-makers and recipients, and making it a priority to ensure that research findings are reflected in real-world settings.<sup>20</sup></p>
</div>    
  
